caption: We always seek out food halls while traveling which is how we ended up here.  This is probably my least favorite food hall we've been to. It's in the design district so it felt very upscale. Food halls tend to be a little pricey, but this one seemed more expensive than most.  We tried Coop, Jaffa, and HotLime Craft Tacos & Ceviche Bar. The food was pretty mediocre. HotLime was the best of the three.  If you want to check out a food hall in Miami, I would recommend going to 1-800 Lucky instead.

Fine/OK establishment. As a previous employee of st roch market for 1 year. (And my choice to leave) I am not pleased with management whatsoever. Very unorganized and dirty. not to mention The infestation issue that went on for months. Not sure much was done about that. As employees come and go you, watch The unsatisfied people leave and new ones come. in my opinion the employees are not valued. Fortunately enough the food in the restaurants make up for it. definitely needs improvement. Wouldn’t recommend. Vendors of st roche are not held to cleanliness standards what so ever. On top of these issues if an employee needed a manager, there is a count of 5 managers. With a team of 5 independent managers You think these issues Like these would be resolved already. So you MUST be sure to contact and speak to each and everyone of them for your concerns. If you can’t not make it to you shift. In the last guest assistant meeting the managers Ryan, axel Kenzie asked employees not to come back to work if they’ve missed a day for whatever reason. You will be treated unfairly if you work here. Honestly the worst place I’ve ever worked.

This is a well-designed food hall with a nice variety of options. They have a bar placed centrally with plenty of indoor seating. The terrace is very nice with additional seating. Food stalls include Mexican, Peruvian, Middle Eastern, Japanese, American, and Italian in addition to vegan and dessert stalls. Overall, prices are on the steep side which is par for the course for these types of places. It's a great choice for a $15-30 meal with several options for all palates.

This isn’t going to be pretty:  My parents and I came to eat at st Roche eatery thinking it was upscale cafeteria food. Jaffa, the purported Israeli food place, we were particularly looking forward to. The Israeli salad in which good quality tomatoes are the quintessential ingredient, was missing about 1/4 of its mass in tomatoes not to mention being flavorless and soggy. The eggplant meat special had very little meat and whatever meat it did have had no seasoning and was particularly bland. They skimped on pita: one tiny piece of pita for four people with several plates of mezze: be emet ben adam? The hummus: canned chickpeas, I say no more. The tahini: mediocre as was the cauliflower they put it on which, despite having the right color, was entirely bereft of flavor. I had two full tins of hot sauce they gave us and devoured both of them as if they were vanilla pudding, because well: they had similar flavor and heat profiles to vanilla pudding 🤦🏻‍♂️. My mom had to go over to their counter twice to ask for more pita and more tomatoes in the salad. Israeli food this is not.

I stopped by for a quick Happy Hour / Friend's Birthday / Sunday Funday, and liked the Mayhaw and its funky cocktails. Located in the center of the St. Roch food court, its concoctions would seem to pair well with almost all of the dishes.  My friends know I like rum, and recommended I try the Fink's Curse. I gotta tell ya, this should be called Fink's Blessing :) What else would you consider a mixture of Plantation Dark Rum, egg whites, and a red wine floatie? It looks like an ice cream slushie, not overly sweet and goes down smooth for a mellow Sunday.  They have a few funky artistic (Parrot and Owl sculptural cups) for other cocktails which I'll try next time.

So far, so awesome for the new St. Roch Market in the Design District. There's about 12 different vendors in a beautiful, spacious hall on the second floor of Palm Court. Unlike other upmarket food courts I've tried, St. Roch's offerings are restaurant level rather than food truck level. The variety is impressive, with everything from ramen to pasta to a raw bar to sushi. Every dish we tried was excellent. The central bar was great as well, with attentive and friendly bartenders crafting unique cocktails. Everyone working at the mini-restaurants seemed genuinely excited about the project and eager to discuss their menus. The atmosphere is exceptionally positive and upbeat, and everyone was particularly kind and friendly to my kids. Outside there's a huge patio with tables and swings. Prices are pretty much in line with Miami upscale, and totally justified by quality. Great place for a family dinner or a killer date.

Amazing! The food hall is beautiful and amazing food! Chefs are amazing! We personally ate at Chloe and Dat Plin and my husband loved the food! If your in the Design District, St Roch Market is a must. Will definately be coming back and trying more awesome food!

The Spice Detective) opened his Israeli-inspired restaurant, “Jaffa” — one of 12 chef-driven concepts. It’s fun and easy to park, shop, wine & dine.  I have a new food destination. Yum!!
